# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2021-scottish-parliament-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Prior to 1707, Scotland and England shared a common monarch but were separate legal entities, so decisions in one did not bind the other.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Although James became king in February 1685 with widespread support in both countries, tolerance for his personal Catholicism did not apply to the religion in general.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] When the Parliaments of England and Scotland refused to rescind legal restrictions on Catholics, James suspended them and ruled by decree.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The birth of a Catholic heir in June 1688 caused widespread civil disorder in Scotland and England and a coalition of English politicians and soldiers issued an Invitation to William.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] They agreed to support Dutch military intervention in order to enforce Mary's rights as heir to the English throne; on 5 November 1688, William landed in South-West England and James fled to France on 23 December.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Despite Scotland's lack of involvement in the Invitation, the veteran Scots Brigade formed part of the Dutch invasion force and Scots were prominent on both sides.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Many of William's advisors were Protestant exiles like Leven and Melville, while James' closest counsellors were two Scots Catholics, the Earl of Perth and his brother Melfort.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] On 7 January 1689, the Scottish Privy Council asked William to act as regent pending election of a Convention of the Estates of Scotland.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In February 1689, William and Mary were appointed joint monarchs of England and in March, the Convention met to agree a similar settlement for Scotland.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] While the Revolution was quick and relatively bloodless in England, a Scottish rising in support of James caused significant casualties and Jacobitism persisted as a political force until the mid-18th century.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In 2016, one of the laws resulting from the Revolution, the Claim of Right Act 1689, was referenced in legal arguments as to whether Scotland was bound by Brexit.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Divergences between the Glorious Revolution in Scotland and England stemmed from political and religious differences between the two kingdoms, which experienced the 1638 to 1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms and 1660 Restoration differently.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Close links between religion and political ideology meant disputes caused huge dislocation and damage; casualties in the Civil Wars were proportionally higher in percentage terms than those later experienced by the United Kingdom in the First World War.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Presbyterian versus Episcopalian now implies differences in both structure and doctrine, but this was not the case in the 17th century.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] *Episcopalian* meant governance by bishops, appointed by the monarch, while *Presbyterian* structures were ruled by Elders, nominated by congregations; in Scotland, both sides were doctrinal Calvinists.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Since bishops sat in the Scottish Parliament, arguments over their role were as much about politics as religious practice.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Changes of regime in 1638, 1651 and 1661 led to the victors excluding their opponents, making the contest for control of the Church of Scotland, or kirk, increasingly bitter.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] As Charles II had no legitimate children, his brother James was his heir.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] James secretly became a Catholic in 1669, and although long suspected, his conversion only became public knowledge in 1679.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] While the Parliament of England attempted to exclude him from the English throne as a result, in Scotland he was viewed with much greater sympathy.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] As a result, while south west Scotland was a stronghold for Covenanter dissidents who opposed James on religious grounds, elsewhere there was little support for Argyll's Rising in June 1685, which was easily put down.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In 1685, James' position in Scotland was more secure than it was in England.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The 1681 Scottish Succession and Test Acts made obedience to the monarch a legal obligation, 'regardless of religion' but in return confirmed the primacy of the Church of Scotland, or Kirk.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Argyll's Rising collapsed due to lack of popular support; repealing the Test Act undermined James' Episcopalian base while rewarding the dissident Presbyterians who backed Argyll.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The perception that James was willing to ignore his commitments, his Coronation Oath and his own supporters undermined his policies.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] They were also badly timed, since the October 1685 Edict of Fontainebleau revoked tolerance for French Protestants, causing an estimated 200,000 to 400,000 Protestants to flee France in the next five years.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The killing of over 2,000 Swiss Waldensians in 1686 reinforced fears that Protestant Europe was threatened by a French-led Catholic counter-reformation.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In June 1688, two events turned dissent into a crisis; the birth of James Francis Edward on 10 June created a Catholic heir, who would precede James' Protestant daughter Mary, married to William of Orange, in the succession.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Though James argued that he merely wanted to increase freedom for Catholics, his prosecution of the Seven Bishops seemed to go beyond this and was perceived as an assault on the Episcopalian establishment; their acquittal on 30 June destroyed James' political authority.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In 1685, many feared civil war if James were bypassed; by 1688, anti-Catholic riots made it seem only his removal could prevent one.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] As events in England rapidly escalated James's chief advisor, the Earl of Sunderland secretly co-ordinated with Henry Sydney to prepare the Invitation to William, assuring him of support from across the English political class for armed intervention.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Anxious to secure English financial and military support against France, William landed in Brixham on 5 November with 14,000 men; as he advanced, much of the Royal Army deserted and James went into exile on 23 December.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] While Scotland had remained relatively passive in the events, once the king fled to France, mob riots in Edinburgh removed Jesuits from the Chapel Royal at Holyrood.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Events in England pre-empted a Scottish solution.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] As the English Parliament offered their throne to William and Mary in February 1689, James remained King of Scots for a further four months until 4 April 1689.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] While in England a large majority agreed that Mary should replace her father, William demanded he be made joint monarch and sole ruler if she died.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In Scotland, the split within the Kirk made William more important; his Calvinism meant that Presbyterians saw him as a natural ally, while the Episcopalian minority needed his support to retain control.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] On 7 January 1689 the Scottish Privy Council asked William to take over government pending a Scottish Convention that would agree a settlement.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] 70 of the 125 delegates elected in March were classed as Presbyterian, with a tiny minority loyal to James; this made the convention a contest between Episcopalians and Presbyterians over control of the kirk and the limits of Royal authority.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] On 12 March, James landed in Ireland and on 16th a Letter to the convention was read out, demanding obedience and threatening punishment for non-compliance.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Public anger meant some Episcopalians stopped attending the convention, claiming to fear for their safety while others changed sides.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Tensions were high, with the Duke of Gordon holding Edinburgh Castle for James and Viscount Dundee recruiting Highland levies.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] This exaggerated the Presbyterian majority in the Convention which met behind closed doors guarded by its own troops.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The Convention of the Scottish Estates met to consider letters received on 16 March 1689 from the two contenders for the Crown.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] On 4 April they voted to remove James VII from office, drawing on George Buchanan's argument on the contractual nature of monarchy.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Later that month, the Convention adopted the Claim of Right and the Article of Grievances, enumerating what they saw as the contemporary requirements of Scottish constitutional law.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] It also declared that, because of his actions in violation of these laws, James had forfeited the Scottish throne.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Thus, he had “forfeited the Right to the Crown, and the Throne is become vacant”.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In an attempt to preserve Episcopalianism, the Scottish Bishops proposed Union with England but this was rejected by the English Parliament.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] On 11 April, the Convention ended James' reign and adopted the Articles of Grievances and the Claim of Right Act that made Parliament the primary legislative power in Scotland.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] On 11 May 1689, William and Mary accepted the Scottish throne and the Convention became a full Parliament on 5 June.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Dundee's rising highlighted William's reliance on Presbyterian support and he ended attempts to retain the Bishops, leading to the 1690 Act of Settlement restoring Presbyterianism.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The Glorious Revolution in Scotland resulted in greater independence for Parliament and kirk but the ending of Episcopacy isolated a significant part of the political class; this would be a major factor in debates over the 1707 Act of Union and the Scottish Jacobite movement.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Key figures in the new government were Lord Melville, who joined William in the Netherlands in 1683 after the Rye House Plot and the Earl of Stair, a former member of James VII's administration.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In 1689, Melville was appointed Secretary of State for Scotland with Stair as Lord Advocate, a combination intended to minimise Presbyterian dominance of Parliament.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The first session was a stalemate over abolishing Episcopacy in the Kirk and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that decided what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] As a result, Parliament refused to approve taxes or nominations for legal officers, effectively closing the law courts and William blocked implementation of legislation by withholding Royal Assent to Acts approved by Parliament.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] A majority of MPs formed themselves into an anti-government group called the club, led by Sir James Montgomery, previously one of William's chief supporters but angered by Melville being preferred as Secretary of State.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] While some like Montgomery simply resented exclusion from office, most opposed the government on political grounds and primarily wanted to eliminate the Committee of the Articles.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The government compromised by agreeing to remove bishops from the kirk but resisted abolition of the Committee of the Articles before Parliament was suspended on 2 August, following the Battle of Killiecrankie.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Parliament reconvened in April 1690 in an atmosphere of high tension due to the Jacobite war in Ireland, fears of an Irish invasion of Scotland and continuing unrest in the Highlands.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] An alleged Jacobite conspiracy called the Montgomery Plot was uncovered, involving Montgomery, the Marquess of Annandale and Lord Ross.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In the resulting panic, Melville agreed to abolish the Committee of the Articles, although it is still unclear how serious the plot actually was.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Its principal objective achieved, the Club disintegrated, and on 7 June Parliament approved an Act ending Episcopacy and a grant of taxes.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The constitutional settlement that emerged from the 1689 and 1690 Parliamentary sessions was less radical than in 1641.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The Crown retained important prerogative powers, including the right to summon, prorogue and dissolve Parliament but in return abolition of the Committee of Articles gave Parliament control of the legislative agenda.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Conflicts between Protestors and Resolutioners during the Protectorate, then Episcopalians and Cameronians after 1660 had left deep divisions while also normalising the eviction of defeated opponents.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The Kirk's General Assembly meeting in November 1690 was the first since 1654 and even before it convened, over 200 conformist and Episcopalian ministers had been removed from their livings.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] This meant the Assembly was overwhelmingly composed of radical Presbyterians who rejected any measure of Episcopalianism or the reinstatement of those already evicted.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Despite being a fellow Calvinist, William was more tolerant towards Episcopalians, seeing them as potential allies while recognising the dangers of alienating an important political constituency.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] However, the Assembly eliminated Episcopacy and created two commissions for the south and north of the Tay which over the next 25 years removed almost two-thirds of all ministers.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The General Assembly of 1692 refused to reinstate even those Episcopalian ministers who pledged to accept Presbyterianism leaving many presbyteries with few or no parish clergy.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] William issued two acts of indulgence in 1693 and 1695 restoring ministers who accepted him as king; nearly one hundred clergy took advantage of this and a further measure of indulgence in 1707 left only a small remnant of Jacobite Episcopalians and some Society people.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The final settlement was closer to that of 1592 rather than the more radical position of 1649 and the degree of independence between Kirk and State remained ambiguous.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Despite the theoretical abolition of lay patronage, heritors and elders retained the right to nominate candidates for their own parishes who could then be "called" by the congregation.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The Scottish Parliament was dominated by Presbyterians, with a small group of Stuart loyalists known as Jacobites from Jacobus, Latin for James.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] This included members of the Roman Catholic minority, conservative Episcopalians or those with personal ties such as Viscount Dundee, his military chief in Scotland.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The vast majority were unenthusiastic about either James or William, while the Jacobites were also split between Protestant and Roman Catholic factions.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Dundee led a campaign in Scotland to support James' landing in Ireland, where clan rivalries or simple opportunism were often more important than allegiance to William or James.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The Presbyterian Macleans joined the Jacobites in order to regain territories in Mull lost to the Campbells in the 1670s, while the Jacobite Keppoch MacDonalds tried to sack Inverness and were bought off only after Dundee intervened.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Despite victory at Killiecrankie in July, the Jacobites suffered heavy losses including Dundee himself.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Organised resistance ended with defeat at Battle of Cromdale on 1 May 1690, although it took another two years to enforce allegiance to the new regime.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The Glorious Revolution settled the dominance of the Presbyterians in the Church of Scotland and the Whigs in politics but alienated a significant segment of the political class.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] The Whig dominance continued in both Scotland and England well into the mid-eighteenth century.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] As in England, the Revolution confirmed the ascendancy of Parliament over the Crown but by removing bishops from the Kirk, it alienated a significant segment of the political class.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] In the long-term, Episcopalianism rather than Highlander or Lowlander was a key determinant of Jacobite support in both 1715 and 1745.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1689-scottish-general-election] Scotland's involvement in the Nine Years' War and the War of the Spanish Succession ultimately led to the Acts of Union and the creation of Great Britain, as the danger of a divided succession between Scotland and England drove the need for a lasting resolution.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] General elections were held in Scotland in 1702 to return members to serve in the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] The new government would be a minority Court Party administration, led by the Duke of Queensberry as Lord High Commissioner.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] The election took place amidst the War of the Spanish Succession, and one of Queensberry's key main priorities was to secure Scottish funding for the war.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] The new parliament assembled in Edinburgh on 6 May 1703.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] Queensberry sought to build an alliance between his Court party and the Episcopalian Cavalier faction, whose parliamentary presence had been increased by the election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] This alliance was in part driven by Queen Anne's own Anglicanism and Stewart heritage.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] For their support, the Cavaliers requested greater toleration for Episcopalians.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] The parliament was still predominantly Presbyterian, and neither Queensberry or his Court faction favoured toleration.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] Any increased support from Cavaliers as a result of a deal would likely be balanced by a loss in support from Presbyterian opponents to toleration.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] At this period elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1702-scottish-general-election] The returning officer in each shire or burgh fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1880-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] A general election was held in the United Kingdom between 31 March and 27 April 1880 and members were returned for all 60 seats in Scotland.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1880-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Scotland was allocated 54 territorial seats, comprising 22 burgh constituencies and 32 county constituencies, and two university constituencies, Glasgow and Aberdeen Universities and Edinburgh and St Andrews Universities.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1880-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] As voters in university constituencies voted in addition to their territorial vote, the results are compiled separately.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1880-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Of particular note was the Scottish-based Midlothian campaign of William Gladstone.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] A general election was held in the United Kingdom between 24 November and 18 December 1885 and members were returned for all 72 seats in Scotland.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Scotland was allocated 70 territorial seats, comprising 32 burgh constituencies and 37 county constituencies, and two university constituencies, Glasgow and Aberdeen Universities and Edinburgh and St Andrews Universities.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Of particular note was the splintering of the Liberal representation in Scotland.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Some 7 MPs were returned as Independent Liberals, with Edinburgh in particular seeing 3 of its 4 constituencies return Independent Liberals.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] In the western Highlands the Crofters Party emerged as the dominant force, taking four constituencies.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The Independent Liberal MP elected for the Wick Burghs also aligned with the group.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The emergence of the group was owed to the Representation of the People Act 1884, which had reduced the property qualifications for voters.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] As a result many crofters were able to vote for the first time in 1885.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1885-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The Crofting Party worked in close collaboration with the Highland Land League, and opposed the lack of secure and tenure and the severely reduced access to land for crofters.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] A general election was held in the United Kingdom over the period was held from 1 to 27 July 1886, and members were returned for all Scottish seats.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Scotland was allocated 72 seats in total, with 70 territorial seats, comprising 32 burgh constituencies and 37 county constituencies.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] There were also two university constituencies, Glasgow and Aberdeen Universities and Edinburgh and St Andrews Universities.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The election was called following the defeat of the Government of Ireland Bill 1886, which led to a split in the Liberal party: Liberals who did not support Home Rule for Ireland formed the breakaway Liberal Unionist Party.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Although the Liberals won a majority of the seats in Scotland, when combined with results from across the United Kingdom the election resulted in the defeat of William Ewart Gladstone's government.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Although the Liberal Unionists did not formally join with the Conservatives, in practice the two groups acted together to control a parliamentary majority in the House of Commons.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The two university constituencies each elected an additional member to the house.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1886-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] In this election both seats were uncontested, with the sitting members being returned unopposed.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The **1892 United Kingdom general election** was held from 4 to 26 July 1892, and members were returned for all Scottish seats.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Scotland was allocated 72 seats in total, of which 70 were territorial seats, comprising 32 burgh constituencies and 37 county constituencies.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Salisbury refused to resign on hearing the election results and waited to be defeated in a vote of no confidence on 11 August.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Gladstone formed a minority government dependent on Irish Nationalist support.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1892-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The election was the first election in Scotland to see meaningful attempts by groups associated with the trades union movement to win seats: the Scottish United Trades Councils Labour Party stood in four seats whilst the Scottish Labour Party (1888) stood in three seats.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The **1895 United Kingdom general election** was held from 13 July to 7 August 1895, and members were returned for all Scottish seats.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] William Gladstone had led the Liberals to power three years earlier, however following his retirement in 1894 the Earl of Rosebery had been appointed as prime minister.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Rosebery's government found itself largely in a state of paralysis due to a power struggle between him and William Harcourt, the Liberal leader in the Commons.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The situation came to a head on 21 June 1895, when Parliament voted to dismiss Secretary of State for War Henry Campbell-Bannerman; Rosebery, realising that the government would likely not survive a motion of no confidence were one to be brought, promptly resigned as prime minister.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Conservative leader Lord Salisbury was subsequently re-appointed for a third spell as prime minister, and promptly called a new election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] Although the Liberals won a majority of the seats in Scotland, they suffered large losses, and when combined with results from across the United Kingdom the Conservatives/Liberal Unionist alliance achieved a parliamentary majority of 153 for Lord Salisbury.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/1895-united-kingdom-general-election-in-scotland] The Independent Labour Party, having only previously existed as a loose grouping of left-wing politicians, formally organised into a party led by Keir Hardie in 1893 and contested their first election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] An election for the Scottish Parliament was held on 6 May 2021 under the provisions of the Scotland Act 1998.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] It was the sixth Scottish Parliament election since the devolved parliament was established in 1999.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] 129 Members of the Scottish Parliament were elected.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The election was held alongside the Senedd election in Wales, English local elections, London Assembly and mayoral election and the Hartlepool by-election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The election campaign started on 25 March 2021, during the COVID-19 pandemic in Scotland.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] As a result, Parliament went into recess on 5 May, the day before the election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Of those five parties, three had changed their leader since the 2016 election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Newer parties set up since the 2016 election included: Reform UK Scotland, led by Michelle Ballantyne; the Alba Party, led by former First Minister and SNP leader Alex Salmond; and All for Unity, led by George Galloway.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] These parties only competed for seats on the regional lists.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The election resulted in the SNP winning a fourth consecutive term in government.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] They won 64 seats, a net increase of one from the 2016 election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP gained Edinburgh Central, Ayr, and East Lothian, as well as winning the largest share of the popular vote and the largest number of constituency seats in any Scottish Parliament election (62).
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Greens won eight seats, their best result to date at a Scottish Parliament election, while the Conservatives retained second place with 31 seats.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Labour had its worst-ever result with 22 seats, and the lowest share of the vote in both constituency and list votes for either Westminster or Holyrood since 1910.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Liberal Democrats also had their worst showing at a Holyrood election to date, winning only four seats.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP and the Greens, both of which support Scottish independence, won 72 of the 129 seats in the parliament.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Unionist parties (that is, those against independence) achieved a small majority of votes in constituency contests, whilst pro-independence parties achieved a small majority in the regional lists.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The turnout was 63.5%, which is the highest ever at a Scottish Parliament election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Following the election, the third Sturgeon government was formed.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] It initially consisted of just the SNP, but later included Slater and Harvie of the Scottish Greens as junior ministers after the two parties negotiated a power-sharing agreement.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] At the 2016 election, the ruling Scottish National Party (SNP) lost its parliamentary majority but was able to continue governing under Nicola Sturgeon as a minority administration.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] At the same election, the Conservatives overtook Labour to place second, whilst the Greens overtook the Liberal Democrats to place fourth.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] No representatives of minor parties were elected to the Parliament.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Three parties had undergone leadership changes since the 2016 election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In August 2017, Kezia Dugdale resigned as leader of Scottish Labour and was replaced by Richard Leonard.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In January 2021, less than four months before the election, Leonard resigned.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Anas Sarwar won the subsequent leadership election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In August 2019, Lorna Slater and Patrick Harvie became co-leaders of the Scottish Greens.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Also in August 2019, Ruth Davidson resigned as leader of the Scottish Conservatives and was succeeded by Jackson Carlaw.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Carlaw resigned as leader in July 2020, with Douglas Ross winning the subsequent leadership election unopposed.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The 2021 election was the first to come after the passage of the Scottish Elections (Franchise and Representation) Act, which extended the franchise to those serving prison sentences of 12 months or less.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In 2005, the United Kingdom was found in breach of Protocol 1, Article 3 of the European Convention on Human Rights in regards to prisoner voting rights in the European Court of Human Rights as a result of *Hirst v United Kingdom (No 2)*; the Act brings Scotland in line with the court ruling.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This act also allows all foreign nationals resident in Scotland to vote and all those with indefinite leave to remain or equivalent status, including pre–settled status in the United Kingdom, to stand as candidates.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] A BBC News report in April 2021 said that there were around 55,000 foreign nationals who had been given the right to vote as a result of these changes, including 20,000 refugees.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Under the Scotland Act 1998, an ordinary general election to the Scottish Parliament would normally have been held on the first Thursday in May four years after the 2016 election, i.e. in May 2020.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This would have clashed with the proposed date of a UK general election, although this became a moot point when a snap UK general election was held in June 2017 (a further UK general election was held in December 2019).
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In November 2015, the Scottish Government published a Scottish Elections (Dates) Bill, which proposed to extend the term of the Parliament to five years.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 25 February 2016 and received Royal Assent on 30 March 2016, setting the new date for the election as 6 May 2021.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Nevertheless, no extraordinary general elections have been held to date.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Any extraordinary general election would be in addition to the ordinary general elections, unless held less than six months before the due date of an ordinary general election, in which case it would supplant it.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This would not affect the year in which the subsequent ordinary general election would be held.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 16 November 2020, the Scottish General Election (Coronavirus) Bill was introduced.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This draft legislation stated that while the next election was intended to be held on 6 May 2021, the Presiding Officer would gain the power to postpone the election by up to six months if the spread of COVID-19 made that date impractical.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The bill also proposed to change the date of dissolution to the day before the election, meaning that the Parliament could be recalled during the election period.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The bill was enacted and received Royal Assent on 29 January 2021.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Parliament was in fact recalled on 12 April, to allow MSPs to mark the death of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] James Dornan announced in February 2020 his intention to retire at the next Holyrood election, but reversed this decision some months later.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP, Conservatives, Labour and Liberal Democrats fielded candidates in all 73 constituencies and all eight of the regional ballots.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Five other parties contested both all eight regions and at least one constituency: the Scottish Greens (12 constituencies) the Scottish Libertarian Party (9), the Scottish Family Party (7), UKIP (5) and the Freedom Alliance (4).
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Four parties – Abolish the Scottish Parliament Party, Alba Party, All for Unity, and Reform UK – stood in all eight electoral regions, but did not contest any constituencies.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Five other parties – Independent Green Voice (5 regions), Renew (5), the Social Democratic Party (2), Women's Equality (2) and Animal Welfare (1) – contested some of the regions, but not any constituencies.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Scottish Socialist Party, which participated in the last election as part of the electoral alliance RISE – Scotland's Left Alliance, opted not to participate in this election, for the first time since its inception.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The total number of Members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs) elected to the Parliament was 129.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Scottish Parliament uses an additional member system (AMS), designed to produce approximate proportional representation for each region.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] There are 8 regions, each sub-divided into 8 to 10 single-member constituencies.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Each constituency elects one MSP by the plurality (first past the post) system of election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Each region elects 7 additional MSPs using an additional member system.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] A modified D'Hondt method using the constituency results is used to elect these additional MSPs.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The boundaries of the 73 constituencies last changed as of the 2011 Scottish Parliament election, as did the configuration of the electoral regions used to elect "list" members of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] These revisions were the outcome of the First Periodical Review of the Scottish Parliament's constituencies and regions conducted by the Boundary Commission for Scotland; the Review was announced on 3 July 2007 and the Commission published its final report on 26 May 2010.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The size difference between Westminster and Holyrood boundaries was due to diverge further upon the implementation of the Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies, which has not been voted upon by Parliament.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The 2023 Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies for a UK total of 650 MPs commenced in England in 2021 and will complete for the UK by 2023.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The election campaign started on 25 March 2021.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Scottish Conservatives launched their campaign the same day, with a focus on promoting Scotland's recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 26 March 2021, the Alba Party was publicly launched by former First Minister of Scotland and SNP leader, Alex Salmond.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The party announced plans to stand list-only candidates.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Two sitting SNP MPs later defected to the Alba party.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Action for Independence party, which had intended to pursue a similar list-only strategy, announced they would stand down their candidates in favour of Alba.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Sturgeon said she would refuse to have any dealings with Salmond unless he apologises to the women who had accused him of harassment.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Salmond was ultimately acquitted of all charges.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] BBC Scotland announced that it would broadcast two debates between the main parties' leaders; the first was aired on 30 March 2021 and was moderated by the corporation's Scotland editor Sarah Smith.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The debate included key questions from the audience on the COVID-19 recovery, climate change, and a second referendum on Scottish independence.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The second BBC debate was held on 4 May 2021 and was moderated by BBC Scotland's political editor Glenn Campbell.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Commercial broadcaster STV held their leaders' debate on 13 April, moderated by their political editor Colin Mackay.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] NUS Scotland held a debate, specifically on student issues, on 20 April; it was moderated by NUS Scotland president Matt Crilly and featured the three main party leaders.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 1 April, Planet Radio announced that their Clyde 2 station would be hosting a Leaders Phone-In with the main party leaders every Sunday before the election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Douglas Ross was the first to be interviewed on 4 April, with Willie Rennie following on 18 April.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Whilst Nicola Sturgeon was set to be interviewed on 11 April, campaigning was delayed following the death of Prince Philip and her phone-in was instead held on 22 April.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Patrick Harvie followed on 25 April; and Anas Sarwar had the final phone-in on 2 May.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Following Prince Philip's death on 9 April, the SNP, Conservatives, Labour, Greens and Liberal Democrats said they would suspend election campaigning until further notice.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] After discussion between the parties, they agreed to resume campaigning after a special parliamentary session on 12 April to make tributes and to pause activities again on the day of the funeral (17 April).
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Graph of opinion poll results prior to the 2021 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Below are listed all the constituencies which required a swing of less than 5% from the 2016 result to change hands.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The most marginal opportunity for the Greens was in Glasgow Kelvin, which they needed a 7.1% swing to gain.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Liberal Democrats' best bet was Caithness, Sutherland and Ross, which required a 6.1% swing.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP ended up holding both of these constituencies.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] (Note: no mechanism is used to have the overall seat counts for each party reflect the party share of the overall vote.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP won 64 seats, falling one seat short of an overall majority.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Some commentators put this down to unionists voting tactically for Conservative, Labour and Liberal Democrat candidates.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In *The National*, Emer O'Toole questioned whether social media adverts with "a lack of transparency over funding" may have cost the SNP key seats as well.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The day before the election, *The Guardian* reported that anti-independence groups and campaigners had "spent tens of thousands of pounds in the past week", including on Facebook adverts, calling for tactical voting to prevent the SNP getting a majority.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Additionally, the Greens claimed that they may have been deprived of two seats because of Independent Green Voice (IGV), a far-right party which has nothing to do with the Scottish Greens (who support Scottish independence).
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] IGV received nearly 10,000 votes, including 2,210 in Glasgow (where the Greens were 1,000 short of gaining a seat) and 1,690 in South Scotland (where the Greens fell 100 short).
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This potentially prevented pro-independence parties from having a 19-seat majority instead of 15 seats.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The *Scottish and Welsh Election Studies 2021*, revealed on 13 June, found that around a third of Scottish voters who decided to vote differently in the run-up to the election did so to stop another party, and that 90% of those who did this did so in a bid to prevent the SNP winning the seat.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Rob Johns, Professor in Politics at the University of Essex, said: "[W]e found a lot more switching than we had expected.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The polls had suggested that not much was changing and obviously the overall election result was almost eerily similar to 2016.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] That can mean that nobody has changed their mind or it can mean lots of people have changed their mind – but these have cancelled out as people have moved in opposing directions.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Nicola Sturgeon was nominated as First Minister by a vote held on 18 May 2021.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Her cabinet was approved by the parliament two days later and thus the Third Sturgeon government, a minority government, was formed.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 3 August 2021, it was reported that a co-operation agreement between the SNP and the Greens was "on the brink of being finalised" and could see Green MSPs take ministerial positions in government.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 19 August, the power-sharing agreement between the two parties was announced.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Under the terms of the agreement, the Greens have two MSPs appointed as junior ministers in the government who are invited to attend cabinet meetings when their portfolios are being discussed.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Greens signed up to the bulk of the SNP's policies, but in areas of disagreement such as international relations and fee-paying schools the two parties are free to publicly disagree.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The agreement states that the Greens support the government on votes of confidence and supply.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] A deal that would see Patrick Harvie and Lorna Slater made ministers was revealed on 26 August, subject to being voted upon by Green Party members.
[src:2021-scottish-parliament-election/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Two days later, members of both parties overwhelmingly voted in favour of the deal.
